    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Armored sleeveless jackets used by infantry from the mid-14th century to the beginning of the 17th century, consisting of small rectangular metal plates, overlapping in vertical strips, mounted on a fabric or hide support in parallel rows, the whole being sewn to a quilted jacket which gave the garments their final shape.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000039541/Tarassuk and Blair, Complete Encyclopedia of Arms and Armor (1979)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Chaqueta blindada sin mangas utilizada por la infantería desde mediados del siglo XIV hasta los inicios del siglo XVII; consistente en una placa de metal pequeña y rectangular, recubriendo en vertical cintas, montada sobre un soporte de tejido o piel en filas paralelas, todo ello estando cosido a una chaqueta acolchada que le daba a la prenda su forma final.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Gepantserde mouwloze jacks die werden gebruikt door de infanterie vanaf halverwege de 14e eeuw tot begin 17e eeuw; ze bestaan uit kleine rechthoekige metalen plaatjes die elkaar in de vorm van verticale stroken overlappen, in parallelle rijen aangebracht op een ondergrond van stof of huid. Dit geheel werd op een gewatteerd jack genaaid waardoor de kledingstukken hun uiteindelijke vorm kregen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099099/Van Dale groot woordenboek (1994)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>十四世紀中至十七世紀初，步兵穿戴之無袖短甲衣，衣服由小塊長方形金屬片交疊成垂直長條狀，平行排列覆於做為支撐用襯底的布料或獸皮上，全件再縫製於軟襯料短上衣即成。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Gepanzerte ärmellose Jacke von der Infanterie von der Mitte des 14. bis zum Beginn des 17. Jahrhunderts genutzt, aus kleinen rechteckigen Metallplättchen bestehend, in vertikalen Streifen sich überlappend, auf Stoff angebracht oder verdeckt in parallelen Reihen angebracht, das Ganze auf eine Steppjacke genäht, welches dem Kleidungsstück seine endgültige Form gab.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
